This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as absolutely essential skills for children and young people in the future.
Now, languages as subjects are organized as well as science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the programs of independent schools and other schools.
A survey by the British Employment Commission and skills conducted in 2014 shows that among the difficulties employers face in recruiting candidates, 17% are linked to insufficient language skills.
Language skills are therefore increasingly vital to preparing young people for their future careers.
With more language-needing job opportunities, these skills are essential in our globalised world.
Regardless of their choice of career, a person who speaks a second language will benefit from a real advantage in the future through this sustainable competence.
Being able to communicate directly with foreigners will automatically place the multilingual person in front of its competitors.
According to a YouGov survey conducted in 2013 among 4000 adults living in the United Kingdom, 75% of them did not control a foreign language enough to hold a conversation. French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage (15%).
