This year, Harvard University has established a new course that allows all first-class students to sleep more and fight against the growing male trend that consists of studying by consuming caffeine all night.
One teacher noticed that most of the students at the world's best university are unable to take care of them.
This course, designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the first of its kind in the United States.
It was after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning that the idea came to him
In the end, a student approached me and said, "Why did you tell me that in the last year?"
She claimed that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
Dispensed for the first time this year, this course explains to students the need to adopt good sleep habits to improve their school and physical performance, as well as their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, Professor of Psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and Director General of University Health Services, stated that the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that the students had a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The class time consists of different interactive exercises.
One of the sections presents the image of a dormitory containing different objects (coffee cups, curtains, basketball, books...) on which students click to know the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical performance and the importance of integrating a routine before bedtime.
In another section, participants learn how lack of long-term sleep can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A map of the campus with interactive icons then invites participants to reflect on their daily routine.
"We know that this will not change the behavior of students instantly.
However, according to us, they have the right to know this information - in the same way as you have the right to know what the effects of smoking on health are," added Professor Czeisler.
According to him, the culture of pride of " spending a white night" still exists, and he adds that modern technology and increasing pressure on students make a growing problem of lack of sleep.
Having sufficient and good quality sleep should be "the secret weapon" of students to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid taking weight, because the lack of sleep puts the brain in an inanition mode, making them hungry permanently.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student in chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design this course after being one of his students last year in Harvard.
He stated that the course had opened his eyes and moved him to insist that he be offered to the entire campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to propose to all third-cycle students to follow a similar curriculum before joining the designated institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students provide an alarm for both sleep and awakening time, and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED light, which can disturb their circadian rhythm and cause sleep disorders.
