National Trust monitors the secret life of bats
New research carried out in a Scottish Highlands field seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
It is hoped that the comments will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and guide future conservation activities.
The study of the National Trust for Scotland researchers will follow common bats and sopranos as well as long-ear brown bats and Daubenton in the Inverewe garden in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed in key locations around the property to monitor the activities of bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using portable detectors.
A professional sound analysis will determine the frequency of the screams of bats and the activities of different species.
A map and habitat report will be prepared to draw up a detailed picture of their behaviour across the territory.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor to the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal the most important habitat areas for bats and how they are used by each of these species.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work such as grassland creation and the best way to preserve forests for bats and other related species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, bat populations have declined considerably over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects the bolts and results in the loss of their habitat.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a risk, as well as kill-mouse papers and some chemical treatments of construction materials, as well as attacks by pet cats.
The bats aren't really blind.
However, given their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated echolocation technique to detect insects and obstacles on their flight route.
Responsible for the protection of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 large gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, the NTS takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who conduct regular surveys, perchuring inspections and sometimes rescues.
The organization also established the first and only reserve of Scottish bats on the site of Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, which houses eight of the ten species of Scottish bats.
David Thompson, the domain manager, claims that the site is the ideal territory for them.
"Here, in Three, we have an ideal place for bats," he says.
"We have old buildings, many old trees and all the good habitat.
But much more remains to be learned about bats, so that the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what bats need to thrive."
He stressed the importance of verifying the presence of bats before the maintenance of the property was carried out, since by destroying it without a single mother's nest, 400 females and young women could be killed or even the disappearance of a whole local population.
The bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, disturb them, or destroy their traps.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish leader of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to provide his assistance.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and many of our species, we don't know what's going on in their populations for now."
