Point info on the red tide: Low concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission indicates a general decrease in the concentrations of the red tide in certain areas of the Tampa Bay region.
According to the CPF, more irregular flowering conditions are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties - which cause fear of declining concentrations.
The red tide covers about 209 km (130 miles) of coasts, from northern Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
There are islands about 16 km (10 miles) off Hillsborough County, but in less sites than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations in or off the county of Pinellas were reported last week, low to high concentrations off the county of Hillsborough, higher concentrations in Manatee County, higher concentrations at the bottom of Sarasota County or at the width, medium concentrations in Charlotte County and low concentrations in Lee County and off the county of Collier County.
Cases of respiratory irritation persist in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No respiratory irritation was reported in northwest Florida last week.
